{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1781471111,"nonce":"CYgQB3Hrv841JVAECMdxDYoRkCM=","title":"Currently a nullable column is declared with a `#[column(nullable)]` attribute on a field whose","message":"value type is the bare `T`, e.g.:\n\n```rust\nexpires_at: C::Type\u003c'scope, SystemTime\u003e,\n```\n\nConsider instead expressing nullability directly in the column type, dropping the attribute:\n\n```rust\nexpires_at: C::Type\u003c'scope, Option\u003cSystemTime\u003e\u003e,\n```\n\n- Single source of truth: nullability lives in the type, where Rust programmers expect it, with no\n  risk of the attribute and the type disagreeing.\n- `ColumnValue` mode's field type would then *equal* the decoded representation (`Option\u003cT\u003e`),\n  removing the macro's special-case `Option\u003cT\u003e` wrapping for row decode.\n- Idiomatic / matches SeaORM (which uses `Option\u003cT\u003e` in the model). Diesel keeps a schema-level\n  `Nullable\u003cT\u003e` separate from the struct's `Option\u003cT\u003e`, closer to today's tag approach.\n\nThe bug a2b1909 (tuple projection of a nullable column decoded as `T`) is fixed independently by\nmaking the column marker's `ProjectionShape::Row` be `Option\u003cT\u003e`. This issue is purely about the\n*declaration surface*; it does not make that fix smaller.\n\nThe core tension stays the same either way: predicate operands want the bare `T`\n(`col.equals(t)`, and comparing a nullable column to a non-null one), while decode wants `Option\u003cT\u003e`.\nToday that is handled by `ExprKind::Value = T` + a separate nullability flag. With `Option\u003cT\u003e` in the\ntype you would still strip the `Option` internally to keep `.equals(t)` ergonomic — i.e. reconstruct\nthe same split, just keyed off the type shape instead of an attribute.\n\n- Proc-macro `Option\u003c...\u003e` detection is **token-based** (a derive macro sees tokens, not resolved\n  types), so it is fragile across `std::option::Option`, `core::option::Option`, and type aliases.\n- Needs `impl HasColumnType for Option\u003cT\u003e` and nullability inferred from the type for DDL.\n- Breaking change to every nullable-column declaration. Pre-1.0 is the cheap time to do it.\n\nDeferred. The a2b1909 projection fix shipped separately and is forward-compatible with either model.\nRevisit this as its own deliberate API change (its own design pass + PR) if the `Option\u003cT\u003e` surface\nis wanted.","files":null}]}